Perform clustering

scATAC-seq data is highly sparse and essentially binary for diploid cells, providing a significant challenge for downstream analyses.

To mitigate these technical effects, we currently provided two options for normalize the Tn5 integration site matrix (cell by windows). The fault normalized method is tfidf. The tfidf indicates TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) normalization method that is a popular technique in natural language processing and information retrieval for weighing the importance of words (terms) in a document within a collection of documents (a corpus). Using TF-IDF normalization on scATAC-seq data, where cells are represented by their accessibility across genomic regions, is advantageous because it addresses both sparsity and sequencing depth variability inherent in single-cell data. By weighting regions based on their accessibility across cells, TF-IDF highlights rare but informative, cell-type-specific open regions, while down-weighting common, ubiquitously accessible regions, reducing noise from non-informative sites. This approach makes cells more comparable by normalizing sequencing depth across cells, improving the biological signal in downstream analyses like clustering and dimensionality reduction. In doing so, TF-IDF normalization enhances interpretability, emphasizes biologically relevant differences, and improves the clarity of cell-type distinctions, providing a refined feature matrix for understanding regulatory patterns across diverse cell types.

The second option is regmodel, which was first introduced in Socrates (https://github.com/plantformatics/Socrates). In brief, this approach corrects technical variation by fitting a generalized linear model that relates binary accessibility counts to per-cell log10 read depths for each peak (y ~ x), where y is accessibility across cells and x is log10 of accessible peaks per cell. By sampling peaks with kernel regression, it learns global quasibinomial parameters with regularization to avoid overfitting, then applies these parameters across peaks, yielding Pearsons residuals as depth-normalized accessibility profiles. Note: 8GB memory is needed to run this example.

Inputs (Required):
1. -script_dir (a script directory downloaded from GitHub: Socrates2/utils/input_other_required_scripts_dir)
2. -ipt_obj_dir (a directory that stores the filtered objects from the Step 2: Load and QC)
3. -o output_dir (mkdir output_dir)

Overall parameters (Optional):
1. -num_var 20000 (Number of variable windows used for the clustering. Default: 20000)
2. min_mtx_rowmean 0.01 (Minimum number of row means of window by cell count matrix. Default: 0.01)
3. -min_cell 1000 (Minimum number of accessible features per cell for cell filtration. Default: 1000)
4. -min_ft_freq 0.005 (Minimum peak accessibility frequency lower quantile cut-offs. Default: 0.005)
5. -max_ft_freq 0.005 (Maximum peak accessibility frequency upper quantile cut-offs. Default: 0.005)
6. -dim_type SVD (Type of dimension reduction for the data. Two options: NMF or SVD. Default: SVD)
7. -num_PCs 30 (Number of PCs used for clustering. Default: 30)
8. -norm tfidf (Normalization method for the data matrix. Two options: tfidf or regmodel. Default: tfidf)
9. -core_doublet 1 (Set a core number for doublet calling. Default: 1)
10. -harmony yes|no (Perform harmony to remove bactch effect for data from different libraries. Default: yes)
11. -lambda 1 (Ridge regression penalty parameter within HarmonyMatrix function. Specify for each variable in vars_use. Lambda must be strictly positive. Smaller values result in more aggressive correction. Default: 1)
12. -theta 2 (Diversity clustering penalty parameter within HarmonyMatrix function. Specify for each variable in vars_use. theta=0 does not encourage any diversity. Larger values of theta result in more diverse clusters. Default: 2)
13. -sigma 0.1 (Width of soft kmeans clusters within HarmonyMatrix. Sigma scales the distance from a cell to cluster centroids. Larger values of sigma result in cells assigned to more clusters. Smaller values of sigma make soft kmeans cluster approach hard clustering. Default: 0.1)
14. rm_temp yes|no (Remove the temp files built by each step. Default: yes)
15. -res 0.5 (Resolution of clustering. Default: 0.5)
16. -only_cluster yes|no (Only open the clustering step. Users can adjust the resolution to obtain UMAP clustering with different cluster count. Default: no)
17. -prefix output (Specify a prefix name for the final output file. Default: output.)
18. -sd_fold (When evaluating replicate consistency after clustering, an additional effect-size threshold is applied. Specifically, the difference between the cell-typespecific mean and the global mean must exceed a predefined cutoff proportional to the standard deviation of cell-type means, scaled by a two-fold stringency factor by default. Default = 2)
19. -rename_lib (If users do not want to use the library names embedded in the cell IDs and instead wish to replace them with the library names defined in input_object_dir, they can set -rename_lib to no. In this case, users must ensure that the Tn5 cell IDs are consistent with the renamed library identifiers. Default: no)

Outputs
1. *.atac.soc.rds
2. *.UMAP.clusters.pdf
3. *.UMAP.library.pdf
4. *.UMAP.nSites.pdf
5. *.UMAP.FRiP.pdf
6. *.UMAP.FRiP.cluster.test.pdf
7. *.UMAP.doublet.pdf
8. *.UMAP.doublet.cluster.test.pdf
9. *.UMAP.TSS.pdf
10. *.UMAP.TSS.cluster.test.pdf

12. *.aft_rD_rHM_UMAP.rds (temporary file)
13. *.aft_rD_UMAP_rDb.rds (temporary file)

Option 1: Run all the steps at once

Users can choose to run all steps at once. The ipt_obj_dir directory should store the output object (*filtered.soc.rds) generated from Step 2: Load and QC. Typically, all replicate objects should be copied into ipt_obj_dir, where this pipeline will use harmony to merge replicates by removing batch effects.

Several parameters are critical for optimizing clustering performance, including -num_var, -dim_type, and -num_PCs.

Generally, the matrix used for clustering is a Tn5 integration site matrix (cells by windows), where each window (or bin) represents a section of the genome. The Tn5 integration site matrix was generated in Step 2: Load and QC by defining -win_size. The -num_var parameter determines the number of most variable windows/bins to include in the clustering analysis.

-dim_type will provide SVD and NMF. Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) and Non-negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) are two popular dimensionality reduction techniques used to simplify high-dimensional data by identifying key patterns. SVD factorizes a matrix into orthogonal components that capture the most variance, helping reduce dimensions while retaining essential information, which is valuable in clustering and visualization. NMF, on the other hand, decomposes a non-negative matrix into parts that additively combine to approximate the original data, creating interpretable, non-negative components ideal for applications where features naturally combine.

-num_PCs provides the number of Principal components (PCs) used for the clustering. PCs are crucial for clustering after dimensionality reduction because they capture the main patterns of variance, distilling the data to its most meaningful features while filtering out noise. This simplified representation highlights essential structure, allowing clustering algorithms to group data points based on real similarities and differences rather than irrelevant or noisy information, leading to clearer and more accurate clusters. Therefore, users could define a different number of PCs to adjust the structure of clustering.

The parameters -min_effect_FRiP, -min_effect_TSS, and -max_effect_doublet are used to adjust the thresholds for determining whether clusters should be flagged as red-flag clusters. Statistical significance was evaluated using a Wilcoxon signed-rank test (with alternative = greater for FRiP and TSS, and alternative = less for the doublet score), combined with an effect-size criterion that reflects the difference between the global mean and the cluster mean. Only clusters with a p value < 0.05 and a global-to-cluster mean difference exceeding the specified effect-size threshold were considered to fail the test and were marked as significant = TRUE (i.e., flagged clusters).

Running:

mkdir input_obj_dir
cp /Path/to/*filtered.soc.rds input_obj_dir

python Socrates2/utils/clustering.py
-script_dir Socrates2/utils/input_other_required_scripts_dir
-o output_dir
-ipt_obj_dir input_obj_dir

Option 2: Clustering with a single replicate

If users have only one replicate, they should set -harmony no to prevent errors.

Running:

mkdir input_obj_dir
cp /Path/to/*filtered.soc.rds input_obj_dir

python Socrates2/utils/clustering.py
-script_dir Socrates2/utils/input_other_required_scripts_dir
-o output_dir
-ipt_obj_dir input_obj_dir
-harmony no

Option 3: Only perform clustering and change resolution

If users wish to adjust the clustering resolution without re-running the entire process, they can set -only_cluster yes and specify an exact value for -res to control the clustering resolution.

python Socrates2/utils/clustering.py
-script_dir Socrates2/utils/input_other_required_scripts_dir
-o output_dir
-ipt_obj_dir input_obj_dir
-only_cluster yes
-res 1
